    <div class=3D"indent"><h3 id=3D"receiving_realtime_text">7.4 Receiving =
Real-Time Text<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/=
xep-0301.html#receiving_realtime_text"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in=
 the document">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h3>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">In order to allow <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/=
extensions/xep-0301.html#preserving_key_press_intervals">Preserving Key Pre=
ss Intervals</a> in incoming real-time text, recipient clients can do the f=
ollowing:</p>
    <ol start=3D"" class=3D"" style=3D"">
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">Upon receiving <a =
href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#action_elements">Action E=
lements</a> in incoming &lt;rtt/&gt; elements, they are added to a queue in=
 the order they are received. This provides immunity to variable network co=
nditions, since the queueing action will smooth out incoming transmission (=
e.g., receiving new &lt;rtt/&gt; while still processing action elements fro=
m a delayed &lt;rtt/&gt;).</p></li>
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">The recipient clie=
nt processes action elements in the queue in sequential order, including pa=
uses from <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#element_w_wa=
it_interval">Element &lt;w/&gt; =E2=80=93 Wait Interval</a>, if supported. =
This is equivalent to playing back the sender's original typing.</p></li>
    </ol>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">If <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-=
0301.html#element_w_wait_interval">Element &lt;w/&gt; =E2=80=93 Wait Interv=
al</a> is supported, excess lag in incoming real-time text can occur when d=
elayed &lt;rtt/&gt; elements get delivered (e.g., congestion, intermittent =
wireless reception). To avoid delayed presentation of real-time text, the r=
ecipient client needs to speed up processing of action elements. This can b=
e accomplished through a variety of techniques, such as shortening the paus=
es ('n' value) in &lt;w/&gt; elements, ignoring excess &lt;w/&gt; elements,=
 immediately outputting action elements that are still queued, and/or keepi=
ng action elements from a limited number of &lt;rtt/&gt; elements queued (i=
mmediately outputting any prior action elements). This allows lagged real-t=
ime text to catch up more quickly.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Upon receiving a <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/e=
xtensions/xep-0301.html#body_element">Body Element</a> indicating a complet=
ed message, it is acceptable for the full message text from &lt;body/&gt; t=
o be displayed immediately in place of the real-time message, and discard a=
ny unprocessed action elements. This prevents any delay in displaying the f=
inal message delivery, however, this may cause a sudden surge of text in so=
me situations.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">If the &lt;w/&gt; element is not supported, re=
ceiving clients can use an alternate text-smoothing method in order to <a h=
ref=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#avoid_bursty_text_presenta=
tion">Avoid Bursty Text Presentation</a> (e.g., time-smoothed progressive o=
utput of received real-time text).</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h3 id=3D"other_guidelines">7.5 Other Guidelines<=
a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#o=
ther_guidelines"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in the document">=C2=B6<=
/abbr></a></h3>
        <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"message_length">7.5.1 Message Lengt=
h<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html=
#message_length"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in the document">=C2=B6<=
/abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">A large sequence of action elements can result=
 in an &lt;rtt/&gt; larger than the size of a message &lt;body/&gt;. This c=
an occur normally during fast typing when <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/exten=
sions/xep-0301.html#preserving_key_press_intervals">Preserving Key Press In=
tervals</a> during small messages. However, if the &lt;rtt/&gt; element bec=
omes unusually large (e.g., macros, multiple copy and pastes, leading to an=
 &lt;rtt/&gt; exceeding one kilobyte) a <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensi=
ons/xep-0301.html#message_refresh">Message Refresh</a> can instead be used,=
 in order to save bandwidth. (Stream compression is another approach.)</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Clients can limit the length of the text input=
 for the sender's message, in order to keep the size of &lt;message/&gt; st=
anzas reasonable, including during <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/x=
ep-0301.html#message_refresh">Message Refresh</a>. Also, large &lt;rtt/&gt;=
 elements might occur in situations such as large copy and pastes. To keep =
message stanza sizes reasonable, &lt;rtt/&gt; can be transmitted in a separ=
ate &lt;message/&gt; than the one containing &lt;body/&gt;.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">For clients that send continuous real-time tex=
t (e.g., news ticker, captioning, speech transcription, TTY/text telephone =
gateway), a <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#body_eleme=
nt">Body Element</a> can be sent and then a new real-time message started i=
mmediately after, every time a message reaches a specific size. This allows=
 continuous real-time text without real-time messages becoming excessively =
large.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"usage_with_chat_states">7.5.2 Usage wit=
h Chat States<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/x=
ep-0301.html#usage_with_chat_states"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in t=
he document">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Real-time text can be used in conjunction with=
 <strong>Chat State Notifications</strong>. It is best to handle <strong>XE=
P-0301</strong> and <strong>XEP-0085</strong> transmissions in separate &lt=
;message/&gt; stanzas. Chat states such as &lt;composing/&gt; or &lt;active=
/&gt; are sent separately from &lt;rtt/&gt; elements.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Chat states are handled as specified by <stron=
g>XEP-0085</strong>. The continuous transmission of real-time text correspo=
nds to a &lt;composing/&gt; chat state. Therefore, the timing of the &lt;co=
mposing/&gt; chat state coincides with the beginning of continuous &lt;rtt/=
&gt; transmission.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"usage_with_last_message_correction">7.5=
.3 Usage with Last Message Correction<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https=
://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#usage_with_last_message_correction"><a=
bbr title=3D"Link to this point in the document">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">It is possible to use <strong>Last Message Cor=
rection</strong> with real-time text. If <strong>XEP-0308</strong> is imple=
mented in concert with this specification, the following rules apply:</p>
    <ul class=3D"" style=3D"">
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">For all &lt;rtt/&g=
t; elements transmitted during composing a new message, the '<a href=3D"htt=
ps://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#id">id</a>' attribute of &lt;rtt/&gt=
; is not used.</p></li>
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">For all &lt;rtt/&g=
t; elements transmitted during editing of the previous message, the 'id' at=
tribute of &lt;rtt/&gt; matches the 'id' attribute of the old &lt;message/&=
gt; stanza containing the &lt;body/&gt; text being edited (see 'Business Ru=
les' in <strong>XEP-0308</strong>). This enables recipient clients to displ=
ay real-time text while the sender is editing the previously-delivered mess=
age.</p></li>
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">Senders clients ne=
ed to transmit a <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#messa=
ge_refresh">Message Refresh</a> when transmitting &lt;rtt/&gt; for a differ=
ent message than the previously transmitted &lt;rtt/&gt; (i.e., the value o=
f the 'id' attribute changes, 'id' becomes included, or 'id' becomes not in=
cluded). This keeps real-time text synchronized when beginning to edit a pr=
eviously delivered message versus continuing to compose a new message.</p><=
/li>
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">The <strong>XEP-03=
01</strong> and <strong>XEP-0308</strong> protocols operate concurrently vi=
a separate message stanzas. Thus, a message stanza never simultaneously inc=
ludes both &lt;rtt/&gt; and &lt;replace/&gt;.</p></li>
      <li class=3D"" style=3D""><p class=3D"" style=3D"">The <a href=3D"htt=
ps://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#body_element">Body Element</a> deliv=
ers a finished new message or a finished message correction (&lt;replace/&g=
t; is used with &lt;body/&gt; in accordance to <strong>XEP-0308</strong>).<=
/p></li>
    </ul>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"usage_with_multiuser_chat">7.5.4 Usage =
with Multi-User Chat<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/exten=
sions/xep-0301.html#usage_with_multiuser_chat"><abbr title=3D"Link to this =
point in the document">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">For simplicity, clients can implement real-tim=
e text only for one-to-one chat, and not for <strong>Multi-User Chat</stron=
g>. However, it can be appropriate to support &lt;rtt/&gt; elements in grou=
pchat rooms, even if not all participants support real-time text, as long a=
s the service allows it (See <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-030=
1.html#support_for_groupchat">Support for Groupchat</a>).</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Participants that enable real-time text during=
 group chat need to keep track of multiple concurrent real-time messages on=
 a per-participant basis. Participants, with real-time text, will see real-=
time text coming from each participant that has real-time text enabled. Par=
ticipant clients without real-time text (whether unsupported or turned off)=
 will simply see group chat function normally on a line-by-line basis, sinc=
e it is <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#backwards_comp=
atible">Backwards Compatible</a>.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Participants that turn off real-time text for =
themselves, can simply ignore incoming &lt;rtt/&gt; and not transmit outgoi=
ng &lt;rtt/&gt;. Participant clients in groupchat receiving an incoming &lt=
;rtt <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#event">event</a>=
=3D=E2=80=99cancel=E2=80=99/&gt; needs to keep outgoing transmission unaffe=
cted during <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#deactivati=
ng_realtime_text">Deactivating Real-Time Text</a> (otherwise, one participa=
nt could deny real-time text between other willing participants).</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">To minimize on-screen clutter of multiple idle=
 real-time messages, clients can hide idle messages, clear old <a href=3D"h=
ttps://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#stale_messages">Stale Messages</a>=
, and/or prioritize the display of the most useful real-time messages. Prom=
inent visibility of real-time text can be assigned to recent typists and/or=
 moderators (e.g., classroom teacher, convention speaker). For the same par=
ticipant logged in multiple times in the same room, see <a href=3D"https://=
xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#simultaneous_logins">Simultaneous Logins<=
/a> for handling this situation. In situations of simultaneous typing by a =
large number of participants, see <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xe=
p-0301.html#congestion_considerations">Congestion Considerations</a>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"simultaneous_logins">7.5.5 Simultaneous=
 Logins<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-030=
1.html#simultaneous_logins"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in the docume=
nt">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">In situations where there are multiple session=
s from the same JID (i.e., simultaneous logins on multiple clients/devices)=
, transmitting of &lt;rtt/&gt; works in one-to-many situations without any =
special software support. For many-to-one situations where there is incomin=
g &lt;rtt/&gt; from multiple sessions under the same JID, <a href=3D"https:=
//xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#keeping_realtime_text_synchronized">Kee=
ping Real-Time Text Synchronized</a> will pause the real-time message upon =
conflicting &lt;rtt/&gt;, and resume during the next <a href=3D"https://xmp=
p.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#message_refresh">Message Refresh</a>, presum=
ably from the active session. This provides a seamless system-switching exp=
erience. A good implementation of <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xe=
p-0301.html#message_refresh">Message Refresh</a> will improve user experien=
ce, regardless of whether or not the client follows <span class=3D"ref" sty=
le=3D""><a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0296.html">Best Practice=
s for Resource Locking (XEP-0296)</a></span>  [<a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/=
extensions/xep-0301.html#nt-idm45597907069088">21</a>]. Clients can choose =
to distinguish the &lt;rtt/&gt; streams (via full JID and/or via &lt;thread=
/&gt;) and keep multiple concurrent real-time messages similar in manner to=
 <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#usage_with_multiuser_=
chat">Usage with Multi-User Chat</a>, with the <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/=
extensions/xep-0301.html#stale_messages">Stale Messages</a> being timed-out=
.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"stale_messages">7.5.6 Stale Messages<a =
class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#sta=
le_messages"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in the document">=C2=B6</abb=
r></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">There are situations where senders pause typin=
g indefinitely. This can result in recipients displaying a real-time messag=
e for an extended time period. It may also be a screen clutter concern duri=
ng <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#usage_with_multiuse=
r_chat">Usage with Multi-User Chat</a>. In addition, it may be a resource-c=
onsumption concern, as part of <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0=
301.html#congestion_considerations">Congestion Considerations</a>.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">It is acceptable for recipients to clear (and/=
or save) incoming real-time messages that have been idle for an extended ti=
me period. There is no specific time-out period defined by this specificati=
on. For <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#usage_with_mul=
tiuser_chat">Usage with Multi-User Chat</a>, the time-out period might be s=
horter because of the need to reduce screen clutter. For one-to-one chat se=
ssions, the time-out period might need to be longer to allow reasonable int=
erruptions (i.e., sender pausing during a long phone call or other interrup=
tion).</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Senders that resume composing a message (i.e.,=
 continues a partially-composed message hours later) can do a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#message_refresh">Message Refresh</a=
>, which allows recipients to redisplay the real-time message.</p>
    </div>
    <div class=3D"indent"><h4 id=3D"performance_efficiency">7.5.7 Performan=
ce &amp; Efficiency<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extens=
ions/xep-0301.html#performance_efficiency"><abbr title=3D"Link to this poin=
t in the document">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h4>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">With real-time text, frequent screen updates c=
an occur. Screen updates are a potential performance bottleneck, since fast=
 typists type many key presses per second. Optimizing screen updates is mor=
e important on slower platforms. The real-time message might be implemented=
 as a separate window or separate display element.</p>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Battery life considerations are closely relate=
d to performance, as the addition of real-time text can have an impact on b=
attery life. If <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#preser=
ving_key_press_intervals">Preserving Key Press Intervals</a> is supported, =
then support for <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#eleme=
nt_w_wait_interval">Element &lt;w/&gt; =E2=80=93 Wait Interval</a> needs to=
 be implemented in a battery-efficient manner. The <a href=3D"https://xmpp.=
org/extensions/xep-0301.html#transmission_interval">Transmission Interval</=
a> can vary dynamically to optimize for battery life and wireless reception=
. For devices where screen updates are an unavoidable, inefficient bottlene=
ck, see <a href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#lowbandwidth_a=
nd_lowprecision_text_smoothing">Low-Bandwidth and Low-Precision Text Smooth=
ing</a> to reduce the number of screen updates per second.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"use_cases">8.
       Use Cases<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://xmpp.org/extension=
s/xep-0301.html#use_cases"><abbr title=3D"Link to this point in the documen=
t">=C2=B6</abbr></a></h2>
    <p class=3D"" style=3D"">Most of these examples are deliberately kept s=
imple. In complete software implementations supporting key press intervals,=
 transmissions will most resemble the last example, <a href=3D"https://xmpp=
.org/extensions/xep-0301.html#full_message_including_key_press_intervals">F=
ull Message Including Key Press Intervals</a>. For simplicity, these exampl=
es use a bare JID, even in situations where a full JID might be more approp=
riate.</p>
